07924nam a22010095i 9781400832033DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102000nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984614481  a97814008320337 a10.1515/97814008320332doi  a(DE-B1597)453534  a(OCoLC)979881689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDT1945 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a352.74300aTruth v. Justice :bThe Morality of Truth Commissions /ced. by Dennis F. Thompson, Robert I. Rotberg.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe University Center for Human Values Series ;v3600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. Truth Commissions And The Provision Of Truth, Justice, And Reconciliation -- tII. The Moral Foundations of Truth Commissions -- tIII. Restoring Decency to Barbaric Societies -- tIV Moral Ambition Within and Beyond Political Constraints: Reflections on Restorative Justice -- tV. Truth Commissions, Transitional Justice, and Civil Society -- tVI. The Moral Foundations of the South African TRC: Truth as Acknowledgment and Justice as Recognition -- tVII. Truth and Reconciliation in South Africa: The Third Way -- tVIII. The Uses of Truth Commissions: Lessons for the World -- tIX. Amnesty, Truth, and Reconciliation: Reflections on the South African Amnesty Process -- tX. Amnesty’s Justice -- tXI. Trials, Commissions, and Investigating Committees: The Elusive Search for Norms of Due Process -- tXII. The Hope for Healing:What Can Truth Commissions Do? -- tXIII. Doing History, Doing Justice: The Narrative of the Historian and of the Truth Commission -- tXIV. Constructing a Report: Writing Up the “Truth” -- tThe Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe truth commission is an increasingly common fixture of newly democratic states with repressive or strife-ridden pasts. From South Africa to Haiti, truth commissions are at work with varying degrees of support and success. To many, they are the best--or only--way to achieve a full accounting of crimes committed against fellow citizens and to prevent future conflict. Others question whether a restorative justice that sets the guilty free, that cleanses society by words alone, can deter future abuses and allow victims and their families to heal. Here, leading philosophers, lawyers, social scientists, and activists representing several perspectives look at the process of truth commissioning in general and in post-apartheid South Africa. They ask whether the truth commission, as a method of seeking justice after conflict, is fair, moral, and effective in bringing about reconciliation. The authors weigh the virtues and failings of truth commissions, especially the South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission, in their attempt to provide restorative rather than retributive justice. They examine, among other issues, the use of reparations as social policy and the granting of amnesty in exchange for testimony. Most of the contributors praise South Africa's decision to trade due process for the kinds of truth that permit closure. But they are skeptical that such revelations produce reconciliation, particularly in societies that remain divided after a compromise peace with no single victor, as in El Salvador. Ultimately, though, they find the truth commission to be a worthy if imperfect instrument for societies seeking to say "never again" with confidence. At a time when truth commissions have been proposed for Bosnia, Kosovo, Cyprus, East Timor, Cambodia, Nigeria, Palestine, and elsewhere, the authors' conclusion that restorative justice provides positive gains could not be more important. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Amy Gutmann, Rajeev Bhargava, Elizabeth Kiss, David A. Crocker, André du Toit, Alex Boraine, Dumisa Ntsebeza, Lisa Kois, Ronald C. Slye, Kent Greenawalt, Sanford Levinson, Martha Minow, Charles S. Maier, Charles Villa-Vicencio, and Wilhelm Verwoerd.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmnestyzSouth Africa. 0aAmnesty. 0aApartheidzSouth Africa. 0aHuman rightszSouth Africa. 0aHuman rights. 0aReconciliation. 0aTruth commissions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBhargava, Rajeev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoraine, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrocker, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenawalt, Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutmann, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiss, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Sanford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaier, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinow, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNtsebeza, Dumisa B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRotberg, Robert I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRotberg, Robert I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSlye, Ronald C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Dennis F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThompson, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToit, André Du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerwoerd, Wilhelm, econtributor.4ctb4h